AU  - M. Yadav
AU  - S. Jena
AU  - C. K. Panigrahi
AU  - A. K. Naik
T2  - 2025 IEEE 5th International Conference on Sustainable Energy and Future Electric Transportation (SEFET)
AB  - Small commercial electric vehicles (SCVs) used for urban logistics create multiple operational hurdles because of their increasing adoption for commercial purpose. The key problem occurs in designing efficient route schedules. Efficient coordination of charging operations remains a challenging task in this system. Electric vehicles have restricted storage capacity, which causes these issues to develop. The restricted charging infrastructure availability creates additional complications in the process. The use of small commercial electric vehicles (SCVs) in last-mile logistics has recently increased dramatically. However, this growth has led to complicated issues with scheduling the best routes between energy consumption, charging limitations, and delivery time constraints. A system combines Mixed-Integer Linear Programming (MILP) with the Nearest Neighbor Algorithm (NNA) to function. The method finds optimum assignments for SCVs between charging stops and routes. Such optimization reduces both operational and energy- related costs. This technique provides enhanced capabilities for managing vehicle weight as well as performing delivery restriction assessment. The optimized route distances, together with improved charging station efficiency and minimized vehicle downtime, are all achieved better through the MILP-based method compared to heuristic methods. MATLAB serves as the implementation platform of the proposed framework while data from real-world logistics is used for validation through tests with different fleet sizes for scalability assessment.
