TI  - Optimal Transfer Station Siting for Municipal Solid Waste Based on a Dual-Level Genetic Algorithm
AU  - Q. Li
AU  - D. Ma
AU  - J. Zhang
AU  - M. Deng
AU  - J. Peng
AU  - N. Yang
T2  - 2025 6th International Conference on Information Science, Parallel and Distributed Systems (ISPDS)
AB  - The rapid growth of municipal solid waste (MSW) in Chinese cities poses significant challenges to sustainable urban management, particularly in western regions where data and infrastructure remain limited. This study develops a multi-stage optimization framework for MSW collection and transportation in Xi’an, Yanta District, by integrating convex hull-based preprocessing with a dual-level genetic algorithm. The framework introduces two methodological innovations. First, convex hull preprocessing reduces the feasible siting region and partitions the service space, thereby lowering computational complexity and guiding the search toward geographically valid areas. Second, a dual-level chromosome structure is designed, where the siting layer is encoded as a binary vector constrained by the convex hull boundary. In contrast, the routing layer adopts permutation encoding for vehicle scheduling. This hierarchical encoding enables simultaneous optimisation of transfer station siting and vehicle routing, in contrast to conventional sequential methods. Penalty functions are also incorporated into the fitness evaluation to handle vehicle capacity and time-window constraints, improving the feasibility of solutions. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework achieves cost reductions, faster convergence, and more balanced vehicle utilisation compared with benchmark metaheuristics such as single-level GA, (Particle Pwarm Optimization) PSO, and (Ant Colony Optimization) ACO. These contributions highlight methodological advances in location-routing optimization and practical potential for scalable decision-support tools in sustainable MSW management and other urban logistics systems.
C3  - 2025 6th International Conference on Information Science, Parallel and Distributed Systems (ISPDS)
DA  - 2025/11/31/Oct.-2
