AB  - To address the optimization layout problem of distribution automation terminals, this study proposes a hybrid optimization method integrating the courtship firefly algorithm with the genetic algorithm. By constructing an economic model and evaluating reliability indicators, a multi-objective optimization function is established. The algorithm employs a two-phase iterative mechanism: In the first phase, genetic algorithm operations (selection, crossover, and mutation) are applied to the initial population for N1 iterations to generate a fitness-optimized solution set. The second phase introduces an adaptive parameter adjustment mechanism from the courtship firefly algorithm to achieve refined search for local optima. With a total iteration count N set for cyclic computation, each iteration synchronously records optimization results from both algorithms. The global comparison ultimately identifies the optimal layout solution. Experimental results demonstrate that this method effectively reduces equipment investment and operational maintenance costs while ensuring power supply reliability, providing a novel solution for distribution automation terminal deployment.
