AB  - With the popularity of electric vehicles and the limited coverage of fixed charging stations, the charging demand of the EVs poses new challenges to grid operation and energy scheduling. Aiming at the problems of long waiting times for electric vehicle charging, low service rates of fixed charging piles, and long charging distances in urban areas, this paper first forecasts the charging load of electric vehicles. It then schedules mobile energy storage vehicles to provide charging based on the load forecasting results. Three scheduling algorithms are compared: a reinforcement learning-based algorithm, an adaptive large neighborhood search algorithm, and the Ant Colony Optimization algorithm. Through simulation experiments, the performance of the three algorithms in key indicators such as service rate, waiting time, total driving distance, and system efficiency is compared. The results show that the adaptive large neighborhood search algorithm performs best in most scenarios, particularly in service efficiency, waiting time, and operational control.
