TI  - AGV Scheduling Problem with Flexible Charging Operations and Limited Number of Charging Stations
AU  - Y. Li
AU  - B. Ren
AU  - L. Liu
AU  - L. Tang
T2  - 2023 International Conference on Networking, Sensing and Control (ICNSC)
AB  - Nowadays, automated guided vehicles (AGVs) are widely used in various fields to fulfill the transportation demands of factories or workshops due to their intelligence, flexibility, and efficiency. Researchers have widely explored AGV scheduling problems (ASP) in recent years. However, most of the contributions on the topic frequently needed to pay more attention to the issues related to battery constraints and recharge. This paper studies the AGV scheduling problem with flexible charging (ASP-FC). Each AGV can only work on one transfer task involving processing time and energy consumption. The AGVs can charge at any battery level. In addition, our study also finds the situation where AGVs wait at the charging stations due to limited availability. An mixed-integer linear programming(MILP) model is established to minimize the maximum completion time(makespan). The commercial solver CPLEX is used to solve the proposed models. Computational results on 153 benchmark instances with up to 200 jobs, 12 AGVs, and 6 charging stations demonstrate the effectiveness and efficiency of the model. In addition, sensitivity analysis is performed in our paper, including the energy consumption of transfer jobs and the number of charging stations, which can inspire managers to schedule optimization in practice.
